  "summary": "Eileen Bondel discusses the merits of amateur investigation with Inspector Bartholomew. Bondel challenges the official ruling that Gerald Wade died from a sleeping pill overdose, noting that Wade's sister insists he never took such medication. In response to her inquiries, Bartholomew provides a list of various secret organizations, including the Saint Sebastian Brotherhood, Wolf Hounds, Peace Fellows, Comrades Club, Oppressed Alliance, Sons of Moscow, Red Sign, Herring Society, and the Decadent Alliance. While expressing concern that her involvement might cause trouble, Bartholomew eventually offers a hint, suggesting that Bill Everly can provide information regarding the \"seven-faced clock.\"\n\nThe following day, Bondel meets Bill Everly for dinner. During the meal, Bill gossips about an American actress named Barbie Saint Moore, who uses a pseudonym from a \"Famous People Dictionary\" and was involved in a dispute regarding the musical play \"Blinded by the Light.\" Bondel shifts the conversation to Jimmy Sycamore and his planned trip to the Double Dragon Church. Bill expresses concern that Sycamore might be manipulated by a politician he calls \"the old codfish,\" specifically identifying Mrs. McCarta, an MP focused on welfare and children. Bill also mentions that an attractive young Hungarian woman will be attending the upcoming party.",
